# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aldehyde
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aldehyde/1-3-5-trioxane] Trioxane can be obtained by the acid-catalyzed cyclic trimerization of formaldehyde in concentrated aqueous solution.
[src:aldehyde/1-3-5-trioxane] Trioxane can be used interchangeably with formaldehyde and with paraformaldehyde, however the cyclic structure is more stable and it can require high temperatures in order to react.
[src:aldehyde/1-3-5-trioxane] It is a precursor for the production of polyoxymethylene plastics, of which about one million tons per year are produced.
[src:aldehyde/1-3-5-trioxane] Other applications exploit its tendency to release formaldehyde.
[src:aldehyde/1-3-5-trioxane] As such it is used as a binder in textiles, wood products, etc.
[src:aldehyde/1-3-5-trioxane] Trioxane is combined with hexamine and compressed into solid bars to make hexamine fuel tablets, used by the military and outdoorsmen as a cooking fuel.
[src:aldehyde/1-3-5-trioxane] In the laboratory, trioxane is used as an anhydrous source of formaldehyde.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The first example of a stable heteroalkene E=C or E=E' (E, E' = P) containing a heavy group 15 element was reported in 1982 by Yoshifuji.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] After the realization of heavier heteroalkenes, the field of organometallic chemistry began exploring the idea of heteroallenes E=C=E' and E=C=C=E', in which one or more carbon atom of an allene is substituted by a heavier atom.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The first of these heteroallenes containing a heavier group 15 element to be reported was synthesized in 1984 by Yoshifuji.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] 1-phosphaallene, also referred to as ethenylidenephosphine or λ3-phosphaallene, was first synthesized using the 2,4,6-tri-t-butylphenyl (supermesityl, or Mes*) moiety as a sterically protecting group.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The most widely known example of 1-phosphaalenes is the Mes* substituted 3H-phosphallene, where a hydrogen is bonded to the terminal carbon atom, which was synthesized by Märkl and Reitinger in 1988.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Some more recent advances made in regards to 1-phosphaallenes include the development of simpler synthetic routes and the discovery of synthetic pathways using phosphaallenes to create molecules that are typically only synthesized through complicated methods.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Multiple synthetic routes to 1-phosphaallenes have been reported.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The most common are Phospha-Wittig-Horner reactions, rearrangement of alkylynlphosphines with a base present, dehydrochlorination of a chlorovinylphospine, and the reaction of lithium with a C,C-dichlorophosphirane.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] More recent synthetic advances include the dehydrobromination of phosphaalkenes the hydroalumination of alkynylphosphines.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The Phospha-Wittig-Horner reaction, first reported by Mathey et al. in 1992, was initially developed as a synthetic route to convert aldehydes and ketones into C-mono and C,C-disubstituted phosphaalkenes, respectively.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] This method was then adapted to rapidly synthesize phosphaallenes by reacting phosphaketenes with an organolithium base, such as lithium diisopropylamide or t-BuOLi.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] n-BuLi is used as a strong base in the synthesis of a phosphaallene.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] A lithium complex can be used to synthesize phosphaallenes.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Like the transition from an alkyne to an allene in organic chemistry, phosphaallenes can be synthesized from alkynylphosphines by adding a strong base such as n-butyllithium (n-BuLi).
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] These complexes are typically useful due to the broad range of stable products that can be obtained from this synthetic route.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Multiple stable phosphaallenes have been synthesized from LiC≡CR and ArP(H)Cl (R = Ph, t-Bu, Me, CH2OSiMe3).
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The basicity of the lithium complex is essential to the success of these reactions.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The dehydrochlorination of 1-chlorovinylphosphine by DBU (1,8-diazabicyclo-[5.4.0]undec-7-ene) yields a variety of results, depending on the structure of the initial chlorovinylphosphine.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Many of these reactions require temperatures between −90 °C and 0 °C to ensure a stable product is formed.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] As many of these reactions are warmed, oligomerization of the phosphaallene occurs.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Other reactions following this synthetic route occur with gas phase reagents at 250 °C.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] In this synthetic route, a dichlorocarbene is first reacted with a phosphaethylene.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The addition of t-BuLi to the resulting 2,2-dichlorophosphirane yields the phosphaallene.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] This route includes an insertion of carbon into the P=C bond of a phosphaalkene.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] (Z)-2,5-dibromo-1-phosphapent-1-ene with the sterically cumbersome Mes* moiety was reacted with t-BuOK to yield the cyclopropylidenephosphaethene product.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Treatment of the (Z)-2,5-dibromo-1-phosphapent-1-ene reagent with a weaker base, EtONa yields a non-cyclic isomer that can undergo cyclization in the presence of t-BuOK.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] In 2019, a new synthetic route for the synthesis of phosphaallenes was reported by Klöcker and coworkers.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The hydroalumination of dialkynylphosphines with different alkylaluminium hydrides resulted in the elimination of dialkylaluminium alkynides and the desired phosphaallenes.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Many of the phosphaallenes Klöcker and coworkers synthesized spontaneously decomposed into less-desired products, but the newly reported synthetic method did allow for the isolation of some highly reactive compounds that had not been isolated previously.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] In 2022, the most notable aspect of 1-phosphaallenes is their reactivity.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes contain three reactive centers: the P=C bond, the C=C bond, and the phosphorus atom.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The P=C bond and the C=C bond are thought to be electronically independent of one another.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] This gives rise to a wide variety of reactivity, which is similar to that of phosphaalkenes.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Without a large steric hindrance, most phosphaallenes quickly dimerize in a [2+2]- or [2+3]-cycloaddition to yield four- or five-membered rings.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Thus, in order to prevent dimerization, a bulky moiety such as Mes* is often used.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Dimerization frequently occurs in a head-to-tail manner, exhibiting coupling between either the two C=C bonds or the two P=C bonds.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The regioselectivity of these dimerization reactions depends on the substituents on the C in the 3 position.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Nucleophilic alkoxide as well as n-BuLi will add to the P=C bond of a phosphaallene.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] As seen in the reaction scheme, the central C atom is the preferred location for proton attack due to the partial negative charge it possesses.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The reaction of phosphaallenes with dichlorocarbenes results in a [2+1]-cycloaddition to the P=C double bond, which results in stable heterocyclic compounds.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes have also been investigated as reagents to form carbenes.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Reacting the phosphaallene H2P=C=PH with acetylene yields a carbene via [3 + 2]-cycloaddition.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Crystal structure showing phosphaallene-transition metal coordination.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes can coordinate in an ɳ1 or ɳ2 fashion depending on the metal and experimental conditions.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Recent studies into the coordination behavior of the 3H-phosphaallene with tungsten (W) show that both stable and unstable phosphaallenes can bond to W through and ɳ1-coordination mode via a P-W bond.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Due to the stabilizing effect of coordination, reacting transient phosphaallenes with W has become a common method to create stable phosphaallenes that can then be characterized.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] These studies have also demonstrated that 3H-phosphaallenes exhibit ɳ2-coordination to Pt via side-on overlap between Pt and the P=C double bond resulting in a three-membered PtPC heterocycle.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Head-to-tail dimerization of 3H-phosphaallene.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Tricyclic phosphine resulting from decomposition via irradiation.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Decomposition of the 3H-phosphaallene occurs at room-temperature to produce several products via P=C (head-to-tail) or C=C dimerization.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] One decomposition pathway results in an unusual tricyclic phosphine which can be selectively formed by irradiating a solution of the phosphaallene, iBu2AlH, and TripP(C≡CtBu)2 in n-hexanes for 60h with a mercury vapor lamp.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Under these conditions, the tricyclic phosphine was isolated in high yield and a purity of >95%.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Recently, two novel 1-benzodihydrophosphetes were synthesized by heating 3H-phosphaallene Mes*P=C=C(H)R (R = tBu, Ad) in toluene at 110 °C for 16-20h.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The resulting 1- benzodihydrophosphetes were not stable unless coordinated to tungsten.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The phosphorus-bound H of the product can be used in catalyst-free hydrophosphination reactions and in the synthesis of bulky phosphine ligands.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Hydroboration is used as a method to reduce unsaturated compounds, and has been used to reduce P-C double or triple bonds in phosphaalkenes and phosphaalkynes.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Hydroboration of the 3H-phosphaallene Mes*-P=C=C(H)-tBu with 1:1 molar ratio of phosphaallene to H3B(SMe2) yielded a di(phosphaalkenyl)borane, and the reaction in 2:1 molar ratio of phosphaallene to H3B(SMe2) yielded the desired product with a B atom bound to two P=C double bonds.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The hydroboration of the C=C bond was preferred over the hydroboration of the P=C bond.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes are typically colorless or pale yellow in color, and are often crystalline in structure; however, few crystal structures have been reported for this class of compounds.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] One compound, ArP=C=CPh2 (Ar =Mes*) was synthesized and characterized by single crystal X-ray diffraction.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] This compound showed a relatively short P=C double bond length of 1.625(4)Å and a short C=C bond length of 1.1327(5)Å, which closely resembles the bond length in an allene.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The crystal structure also showed a bent geometry with the P=C=C bond angle at 168.0(3)°.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] This bent geometry is thought to be a result of both steric and electronic effects.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] One possible explanation for the observed bent geometry is the bonding model postulated by Lappert et al. which described the bonding between P and the C as singlet states that act in a double π-donor-acceptor fashion.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The crystal structure of another 1-phosphaallene RP=C=CHR' (R= Mes*, R' = tBu) displays the same bent geometry with the P=C=C bond angle being reported as 170.7°.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] Further, this compound also contains a short P=C bond length (1.634Å) and a short C=C bond length (1.136Å).
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The electronic structure of 1-phosphaallene is nearly identical to that of phosphaalkene.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The HOMO in both molecules is the π-orbital of the C=P bond, which is primarily P in character.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The LUMO in both structures, is also heavily localized over the C=P bond.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] However, the dipole moment in phosphaallenes is larger than that of phosphaalkenes.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] In compounds with the antisymmetric form X=C=Y, IR stretching bands are observed in the 1600–2300 cm−1 region.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] However, the IR spectra of 1-phosphaallenes do not contain bands in this region, which suggests that the phosphaallene P=C=C is relatively symmetric.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] In the phosphaallene H2C=C=PH, stretching frequencies are observed at 1788 and 789 cm−1, which are attributed to the C=C bond and the C=P bond, respectively.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] In similar compounds containing a C=C=N skeleton, there is a very strong band present within the 1600 – 2300 cm−1 region.
[src:aldehyde/1-phosphaallenes] The presence of two stretching frequencies rather than one strong frequency in the phosphaallene supports that the C=C and C=P bonds are nearly independent of one another electronically.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] DNPH is a reagent in instructional analytical chemistry laboratories.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] **Brady's reagent** or **Borche's reagent**, is prepared by dissolving DNPH in a solution containing methanol and some concentrated sulfuric acid.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] This solution is used to detect ketones and aldehydes.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] A positive test is signalled by the formation of a yellow, orange or red precipitate of the dinitrophenylhydrazone.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] Aromatic carbonyls give red precipitates whereas aliphatic carbonyls give more yellow color.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] This reaction is, overall, a condensation reaction as two molecules joining together with loss of water.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] DNP-derived hydrazones have characteristic melting points, facilitating identification of the carbonyl.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] In particular, the use of DNPH was developed by Brady and Elsmie.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] Modern spectroscopic and spectrometric techniques have superseded these techniques.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] DNPH does not react with other carbonyl-containing functional groups such as carboxylic acids, amides, and esters, for which there is resonance-associated stability as a lone-pair of electrons interacts with the p orbital of the carbonyl carbon resulting in increased delocalization in the molecule.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] This stability would be lost by addition of a reagent to the carbonyl group.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] Hence, these compounds are more resistant to addition reactions.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] Also, with carboxylic acids, there is the effect of the compound acting as a base, leaving the resulting carboxylate negatively charged and hence no longer vulnerable to nucleophilic attack.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] Dry DNPH is friction and shock sensitive.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] For this reason, it is supplied damp or ‘wetted’ when a school purchases it from a chemical supplier.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] If DNPH is stored improperly and left to dry out, it can become explosive.
[src:aldehyde/2-4-dinitrophenylhydrazine] In 2016, following UK government advice for schools to check for dried out DNPH, bomb disposal teams carried out 589 controlled explosions at UK schools to dispose of potentially hazardous DNPH.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] The branching in 2-ethylhexanol inhibits crystallization.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] Esters of 2-ethylhexanol are similarly affected, which together with low volatility, is the basis of applications in the production of plasticizers and lubricants, where its presence helps reduce viscosity and lower freezing points.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] Because 2-ethylhexanol is a fatty alcohol, its esters have emollient properties.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] Representative is the diester bis(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (DEHP), commonly used in PVC.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] The triester tris (2-Ethylhexyl) trimellitate (TOTM) is another common plasticizer produced via the esterification of three 2-ethylhexanol per trimellitic acid.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] It is also commonly used as a low volatility solvent.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] The nitrate ester of 2-Ethylhexanol is also used as a cetane improver for diesel fuel.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] It also used to react with epichlorohydrin and sodium hydroxide to produce 2-Ethylhexyl glycidyl ether which is then used as an epoxy reactive diluent in various coatings, adhesives and sealants applications.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] It can be used in the development of photos, production of rubber and extraction of oil and gas.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] 2-Ethylhexanol is produced industrially by the hydrogenation of 2-ethylhexanal.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] About 2,500,000 tons are prepared in this way annually.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] 2-Ethylhexanol exhibits low toxicity in animal models, with LD50 ranging from 2-3 g/kg (rat).
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] 2-Ethylhexanol has been identified as a cause of indoor air quality related health problems, such as respiratory system irritation, as a volatile organic compound.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] 2-Ethylhexanol is emitted to air from a PVC flooring installed on concrete that had not been dried properly.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] 2-Ethylhexanol has been linked to developmental toxicity (increased incidence of skeletal malformations in fetuses).
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] This is thought to be a result of metabolism of 2-ethylhexanol into 2-ethylhexanoic acid via oxidation of the primary alcohol.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] The teratogenicity of 2-ethylhexanoic acid, as well as similar substances such as valproic acid, has been well established.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] Although **isooctanol** (and the derived isooctyl prefix) is commonly used in industry to refer to 2-ethylhexanol and its derivatives, IUPAC naming conventions dictate that this name is properly applied to another isomer of octanol, 6-methylheptan-1-ol.
[src:aldehyde/2-ethylhexanol] The Chemical Abstracts Service likewise indexes isooctanol (CAS# 26952-21-6) as 6-methylheptan-1-ol.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] IBX can be prepared in a single step by adding an excess of oxone to an aqueous solution of 2-iodobenzoic acid.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] After warming the solution to 70°C for three hours, the precipitated IBX is collected as a white crystalline solid (80% yield, ≥95% purity).
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] Decomposition of IBX to 2-iodosobenzoic acid and 2-iodobenzoic acid occurs at elevated temperatures, and therefore purification by recrystallization from water is not possible.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] Purity can be increased (≥99%) by shorting the reaction time to one hour at 70°C, at the cost of slightly reducing yield to 77%.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] The reaction mechanism for an oxidation of an alcohol to an aldehyde according to the hypervalent twisting mechanism involves a ligand exchange reaction replacing the hydroxyl group by the alcohol followed by a twist and an elimination reaction.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] The twist is a requirement because the iodine to oxygen double bond is oriented out of plane with the alkoxy group and the concerted elimination would not be able to take place.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] This twist reaction is a rearrangement in which the oxygen atom is moved into a proper plane for a 5 membered cyclic transition state in the elimination reaction and is calculated by Computational chemistry to be the rate-determining step in the oxidation.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] The twist mechanism also explains why oxidation is faster for larger alcohols than for small alcohols.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] The twist is driven forward by the steric hindrance that exists between the ortho hydrogen atom and the protons from the alkoxy group and larger alkoxy groups create larger steric repulsion.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] The same computation predicts a much faster reacting IBX derivative with a 100 fold reaction rate when this ortho hydrogen atom is replaced by a methyl group thus facilitating the twist until the elimination reaction takes prevalence as the rate determining step.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] IBX exists as two tautomers, one of which is the carboxylic acid.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] The acidity of IBX which has been determined in water (pKa 2.4) and DMSO (pKa 6.65) is known to affect organic reactions, for instance acid-catalyzed isomerization accompanying oxidations.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] IBX is also available as silica gel or polystyrene bound IBX.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] In many applications, IBX is replaced by Dess–Martin periodinane which is more soluble in common organic solvents.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] A sample reaction is an IBX oxidation used in the total synthesis of eicosanoid: More and Finney and Van Arman have demonstrated that common organic solvents are suitable for many IBX oxidations, despite its low solubility, and in fact may simplify product purification.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] Nicolaou and co-workers published a series of papers in the *Journal of the American Chemical Society* demonstrating, among other transformations, the use of IBX to oxidize primary and secondary benzylic carbons to aromatic aldehydes and ketones, respectively.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] The presence of additional water in the solution is now considered to be an essential part of those oxidations.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] IBX is notable for oxidizing vicinal diols (or glycols) to diketones without cleavage of the carbon-carbon bond, but oxidative cleavage of glycols to two aldehydes or ketones can occur when modified conditions are used (elevated temperatures or trifluoroacetic acid solvent).
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] The reaction mechanism for this glycol cleavage is based on initial formation of an adduct between 10-I-4 IBX and DMSO to a 12-I-5 intermediate **3** in which DMSO acts as a leaving group for incoming alcohol **4** to intermediate **5**.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] One equivalent of water is split off forming 12-I-5 spirobicyclic periodinane **6** setting the stage for fragmentation to **7**.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] With hydroxyl alpha protons present, oxidation to the acyloin competes.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] Trifluoroacetic acid is found to facilitate the overall reaction.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] Kirsch and co-workers were able to hydroxylate keto compounds with IBX in α-position under mild conditions.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] This method could be extended to β-keto esters, and forms a regioselective way to introduce conjugatively activated unsaturation.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] Bartlett and Beaudry discovered that IBX is a valuable reagent for the transformation of β-hydroxyketones to β-diketones.
[src:aldehyde/2-iodoxybenzoic-acid] IBX provides yields superior to both the Swern and Dess–Martin oxidation protocols.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] α-Hydroxy acids are stronger acids compared to their non-alpha hydroxy counterparts, a property enhanced by internal hydrogen bonding.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] AHAs serve a dual purpose: industrially, they are utilized as additives in animal feed and as precursors for polymer synthesis.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] In cosmetics, they are commonly used for their ability to chemically exfoliate the skin.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] Aldonic acids, a type of sugar acid, are a class of naturally occurring hydroxycarboxylic acids.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] They have the general chemical formula, HO2C(CHOH)*n*CH2OH.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] Gluconic acid, a particularly common aldonic acid, the oxidized derivative of glucose.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] 2-Hydroxy-4-(methylthio)butyric acid is an intermediate in the biosynthesis of 3-dimethylsulfoniopropionate, precursor to natural dimethyl sulfide.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] One common synthesis hydrolyzes the relatively common α-halocarboxylic acids to produce 2-hydroxycarboxylic acids.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] Further specialized synthetic routes are the reaction of dilithiated carboxylic acids with oxygen, followed by neutralization...
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] The synthesis and utilization of polymers based on lactic acid, including polylactic acid (PLA) and its cyclic ester lactide, are used in the creation of biodegradable materials such as medical implants, drug delivery systems, and sutures.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] Similarly, glycolic acid serves as a foundation for the development of poly(glycolic acid), spelled polyglycolide (PGA), a polymer distinguished by its high crystallinity, thermal stability, and mechanical strength, despite its synthetic origins.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] Both PLA and PGA are fully biodegradable.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] Furthermore, mandelic acid, another alpha hydroxy acid, when combined with sulfuric acid produces "SAMMA", obtained via condensation with sulfuric acid.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] Early laboratory work performed in 2002 and 2007 against notable pathogens such as the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and the herpes simplex virus (HSV) suggest SAMMA warrants further investigation as a topical microbicide to prevent vaginal sexually-transmitted infection transmission.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] 2-Hydroxy-4-(methylthio)butyric acid, alpha hydroxy carboxylic acid, is used commercially in a racemic mixture to substitute for methionine in animal feed.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] α-Hydroxy acids, such as glycolic acid, lactic acid, citric acid, and mandelic acid, serve as precursors in organic synthesis, playing a role in the industrial-scale preparation of various compounds.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] These acids are used when synthesizing aldehydes through oxidative cleavage. α-Hydroxy acids are particularly prone to acid-catalyzed decarbonylation, yielding carbon monoxide, a ketone or aldehyde, and water as by-products.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] Alpha hydroxy acids are generally safe when used on the skin as a cosmetic agent using the recommended dosage.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] The most common side-effects are mild skin irritations, redness and flaking.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] The United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and Cosmetic Ingredient Review expert panels both suggest that alpha hydroxy acids are safe to use as long as they are sold at low concentrations, pH levels greater than 3.5, and include thorough safety instructions.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] The FDA has warned consumers that care should be taken when using alpha hydroxy acids after an industry-sponsored study found that they can increase the likelihood of sunburns.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] This effect is reversible after stopping the use of alpha hydroxy acids.
[src:aldehyde/a-hydroxy-acid] Other sources suggest that glycolic acid, in particular, may protect from sun damage.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] In organic chemistry, an **acetal** is a functional group with the connectivity R2C(OR')2.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Here, the R groups can be organic fragments (a carbon atom, with arbitrary other atoms attached to that) or hydrogen, while the R' groups must be organic fragments, not hydrogen.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] The two R' groups can be equivalent to each other (a "symmetric acetal") or not (a "mixed acetal").
[src:aldehyde/acetal] An acetal is formed from and convertible to two alcohol molecules and an aldehyde or ketone, but acetals have substantially different chemical stability and reactivity as compared to the analogous carbonyl compounds.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] The central carbon atom has four bonds to it, and is therefore saturated and has tetrahedral geometry.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] The IUPAC originally deprecated the usage of the word ketal altogether, but has since reversed its decision.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] However, in contrast to historical usage, ketals are now a subset of acetals, a term that now encompasses both aldehyde- and ketone-derived structures.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] If one of the R groups has an oxygen as the first atom (that is, there are more than two oxygens single-bonded to the central carbon), the functional group is instead an orthoester.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] In contrast to variations of R, both R' groups are organic fragments.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] If one R' is a hydrogen, the functional group is instead a hemiacetal, while if both are H, the functional group is a ketone hydrate or aldehyde hydrate.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Formation of an acetal occurs when the hydroxyl group of a hemiacetal becomes protonated and is lost as water.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] The carbocation that is produced is then rapidly attacked by a molecule of alcohol.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Loss of the proton from the attached alcohol gives the acetal.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Acetals are stable compared to hemiacetals but their formation is a reversible equilibrium as with esters.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] As a reaction to create an acetal proceeds, water must be removed from the reaction mixture, for example, with a Dean–Stark apparatus, lest it hydrolyse the product back to the hemiacetal.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] The formation of acetals reduces the total number of molecules present (carbonyl + 2 alcohol → acetal + water) and therefore is generally not favourable with regard to entropy.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] One situation where the reaction is not entropically unfavourable is when a single diol molecule is used rather than two separate alcohol molecules (carbonyl + diol → acetal + water).
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Acetalization and ketalization are the organic reactions that involve the formation of an acetal (or ketals) from aldehydes and ketones, respectively.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Since each step is often a rapid equilibrium, the reaction must be driven by removal of water.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Methods for removing water include azeotropic distillation and trapping water with desiccants like aluminium oxide and molecular sieves.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Steps assumed to be involved: protonation of the carbonyl oxygen, addition of the alcohol to the protonated carbonyl, protonolysis of the resulting hemiacetal or hemiketal, and addition of the second alcohol.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Another way to avoid the entropic cost is to perform the synthesis by acetal exchange (**transacetalization**), using a pre-existing acetal-type reagent as the OR'-group donor rather than simple addition of alcohols themselves.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] One type of reagent used for this method is an orthoester.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] In this case, water produced along with the acetal product is destroyed when it hydrolyses residual orthoester molecules, and this side reaction also produces more alcohol to be used in the main reaction.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Since many sugars are polyhydroxy aldehydes and ketones, sugars are a rich source of acetals and ketals.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Most glycosidic bonds in carbohydrates and other polysaccharides are acetal linkages.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Cellulose is a ubiquitous example of a polyacetal.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Benzylidene acetal and acetonide as protecting groups used in research of modified sugars.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Acetals also find application as chiral auxiliaries.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Indeed acetals of chiral glycols like, e.g. derivatives of tartaric acid can be asymmetrically opened with high selectivity.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] This enables the construction of new chiral centers.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Formaldehyde forms a rich collection of acetals.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] This tendency reflects the fact that low molecular weight aldehydes are prone to self-condensation such that the C=O bond is replaced by an acetal.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] The acetal formed from formaldehyde (two hydrogens attached to the central carbon) is sometimes called a *formal* or the methylenedioxy group.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] The acetal formed from acetone is sometimes called an acetonide.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Formaldehyde forms paraformaldehyde and 1,3,5-trioxane.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Polyoxymethylene (POM) plastic, also known as "acetal" or "polyacetal", is a polyacetal (and a polyether), and a polymer of formaldehyde.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Acetaldehyde converts to paraldehyde and metaldehyde.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Phenylsulfonylethylidene (PSE) acetal is an example of arylsulfonyl acetal possessing atypical properties, like resistance to acid hydrolysis which leads to selective introduction and removal of the protective group.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] 1,1-Diethoxyethane (acetaldehyde diethyl acetal), sometimes called simply "acetal", is an important flavouring compound in distilled beverages.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Two ketals of ethyl acetoacetate are used in commercial fragrances.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Fructone (CH3C(O2C2H4)CH2CO2C2H5), an ethylene glycol ketal, and fraistone (CH3C(O2C2H3CH3)CH2CO2C2H5), a propylene glycol ketal, are commercial fragrances.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] Used in a more general sense, the term **X**,**Y**-*acetal* also refers to any functional group that consists of a carbon bearing two heteroatoms **X** and **Y**.
[src:aldehyde/acetal] For example, *N*,*O*-acetal refers to compounds of type R1R2C(OR)(NR'2) (R,R' ≠ H) also known as a *hemiaminal ether* or aminal, a.k.a. aminoacetal.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In organic chemistry, an **aldehyde** (/ˈældɪhaɪd/) (lat.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] *al*cohol *dehyd*rogenatum, dehydrogenated alcohol) is an organic compound containing a functional group with the structure R−CH=O.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The functional group itself (without the "R" side chain) can be referred to as an **aldehyde** but can also be classified as a **formyl group**.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Aldehydes are a common motif in many chemicals important in technology and biology.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Aldehyde molecules have a central carbon atom that is connected by a double bond to oxygen, a single bond to hydrogen and another single bond to a third substituent, which is carbon or, in the case of formaldehyde, hydrogen.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The central carbon is often described as being sp2-hybridized.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The C=O bond length is about 120–122 picometers.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Aldehydes have properties that are diverse and that depend on the remainder of the molecule.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Smaller aldehydes such as formaldehyde and acetaldehyde are soluble in water, and the volatile aldehydes have pungent odors.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Aldehydes can be identified by spectroscopic methods.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Using IR spectroscopy, they display a strong *ν*CO band near 1700 cm−1.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In their 1H NMR spectra, the formyl hydrogen center absorbs near *δ*H 9.5 to 10, which is a distinctive part of the spectrum.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] This signal shows the characteristic coupling to any protons on the α carbon with a small coupling constant typically less than 3.0 Hz.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The 13C NMR spectra of aldehydes and ketones gives a suppressed (weak) but distinctive signal at *δ*C 190 to 205.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Important aldehydes and related compounds.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Traces of many aldehydes are found in essential oils and often contribute to their pleasant odours, including cinnamaldehyde, cilantro, and vanillin.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Possibly due to the high reactivity of the formyl group, aldehydes are not commonly found in organic "building block" molecules, such as amino acids, nucleic acids, and lipids.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] However, most sugars are derivatives of aldehydes.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] These aldoses exist as hemiacetals, a sort of masked form of the parent aldehyde.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] For example, in aqueous solution only a tiny fraction of glucose exists as the aldehyde.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Of the several methods for preparing aldehydes, one dominant technology is hydroformylation.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Hydroformylation is conducted on a very large scale for diverse aldehydes.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] It involves treatment of the alkene with a mixture of hydrogen gas and carbon monoxide in the presence of a metal catalyst.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The largest operations involve methanol and ethanol respectively to formaldehyde and acetaldehyde, which are produced on multimillion ton scale annually.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Other large scale aldehydes are produced by autoxidation of hydrocarbons: benzaldehyde from toluene, acrolein from propylene, and methacrolein from isobutene.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In the Wacker process, oxidation of ethylene to acetaldehyde in the presence of copper and palladium catalysts, is also used.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] "Green" and cheap oxygen (or air) is the oxidant of choice.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Laboratories may instead apply a wide variety of specialized oxidizing agents, which are often consumed stoichiometrically.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Oxidation can be achieved by heating the alcohol with an acidified solution of potassium dichromate.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In this case, excess dichromate will further oxidize the aldehyde to a carboxylic acid, so either the aldehyde is distilled out as it forms (if volatile) or milder reagents such as PCC are used.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] A variety of reagent systems achieve aldehydes under chromium-free conditions.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] One such are the hypervalent organoiodine compounds (i.e., IBX acid, Dess–Martin periodinane), although these often also oxidize the α position.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] A Lux-Flood acid will activate various sulfoxides (e.g. the Swern oxidation), and amine oxides convert alkyl halides to aldehydes (e.g., the Ganem oxidation).
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Sterically-hindered nitroxyls (i.e., TEMPO) can catalyze aldehyde formation with a cheaper oxidant.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Alternatively, vicinal diols or their oxidized sequelae (acyloins or α-hydroxy acids) can be oxidized with cleavage to two aldehydes or an aldehyde and carbon dioxide.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Aldehydes participate in many reactions.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] From the biological perspective, the key reactions involve addition of nucleophiles to the formyl carbon in the formation of imines (oxidative deamination) and hemiacetals (structures of aldose sugars).
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Because of resonance stabilization of the conjugate base, an α-hydrogen in an aldehyde is weakly acidic with a p*K*a near 17.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The formyl proton itself does not readily undergo deprotonation.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Aldehydes (except those without an alpha carbon, or without protons on the alpha carbon, such as formaldehyde and benzaldehyde) can exist in either the keto or the enol tautomer.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Keto–enol tautomerism is catalyzed by either acid or base.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In neutral solution, the enol is the minority tautomer, reversing several times per second.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] But it becomes the dominant tautomer in strong acid or base solutions, and enolized aldehydes undergo nucleophilic attack at the α position.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The formyl group can be readily reduced to a primary alcohol (−CH2OH).
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Typically this conversion is accomplished by catalytic hydrogenation either directly or by transfer hydrogenation.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Stoichiometric reductions are also popular, as can be effected with sodium borohydride.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The formyl group readily oxidizes to the corresponding carboxyl group (−COOH).
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The preferred oxidant in industry is oxygen or air.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In the laboratory, popular oxidizing agents include potassium permanganate, nitric acid, chromium(VI) oxide, and chromic acid.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The combination of manganese dioxide, cyanide, acetic acid and methanol will convert the aldehyde to a methyl ester.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Another oxidation reaction is the basis of the *silver-mirror test*.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] This reagent converts aldehydes to carboxylic acids without attacking carbon–carbon double bonds.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The name *silver-mirror test* arises because this reaction produces a precipitate of silver, whose presence can be used to test for the presence of an aldehyde.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] A further oxidation reaction involves Fehling's reagent as a test.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The Cu2+ complex ions are reduced to a red-brick-coloured Cu2O precipitate.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Aromatic aldehydes, such as benzaldehyde, do not give a positive Fehling's test, because they are not easily oxidized by mild oxidizing agents like Fehling's reagent.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The benzene ring provides stability, while steric hindrance prevents the formation of the required hydrated anion intermediate.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] If the aldehyde cannot form an enolate (e.g., benzaldehyde), addition of strong base induces the Cannizzaro reaction.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] This reaction results in disproportionation, producing a mixture of alcohol and carboxylic acid.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Nucleophiles add readily to the carbonyl group.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In many cases, a water molecule is removed after the addition takes place; in this case, the reaction is classed as an addition–elimination or addition–condensation reaction.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] There are many variations of nucleophilic addition reactions.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In the acetalisation reaction, under acidic or basic conditions, an alcohol adds to the carbonyl group and a proton is transferred to form a hemiacetal.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Under acidic conditions, the hemiacetal and the alcohol can further react to form an acetal and water.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Simple hemiacetals are usually unstable, although cyclic ones such as glucose can be stable.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Acetals are stable, but revert to the aldehyde in the presence of acid.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Aldehydes can react with water to form hydrates, R−CH(OH)2.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] These diols are stable when strong electron withdrawing groups are present, as in chloral hydrate.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The mechanism of formation is identical to hemiacetal formation.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Another aldehyde molecule can also act as the nucleophile to give polymeric or oligomeric acetals called paraldehydes.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In alkylimino-de-oxo-bisubstitution, a primary or secondary amine adds to the carbonyl group and a proton is transferred from the nitrogen to the oxygen atom to create a carbinolamine.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In the case of a primary amine, a water molecule can be eliminated from the carbinolamine intermediate to yield an imine or its trimer, a hexahydrotriazine This reaction is catalyzed by acid.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Hydroxylamine (NH2OH) can also add to the carbonyl group.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] After the elimination of water, this results in an oxime.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] An ammonia derivative of the form H2NNR2 such as hydrazine (H2NNH2) or 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine can also be the nucleophile and after the elimination of water, resulting in the formation of a hydrazone, which are usually orange crystalline solids.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] This reaction forms the basis of a test for aldehydes and ketones.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The cyano group in HCN can add to the carbonyl group to form cyanohydrins, R−CH(OH)CN.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In this reaction the CN− ion is the nucleophile that attacks the partially positive carbon atom of the carbonyl group.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The mechanism involves a pair of electrons from the carbonyl-group double bond transferring to the oxygen atom, leaving it single-bonded to carbon and giving the oxygen atom a negative charge.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] This intermediate ion rapidly reacts with H+, such as from the HCN molecule, to form the alcohol group of the cyanohydrin.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Organometallic compounds, such as organolithium reagents, Grignard reagents, or acetylides, undergo nucleophilic addition reactions, yielding a substituted alcohol group.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Related reactions include organostannane additions, Barbier reactions, and the Nozaki–Hiyama–Kishi reaction.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In the aldol reaction, the metal enolates of ketones, esters, amides, and carboxylic acids add to aldehydes to form β-hydroxycarbonyl compounds (aldols).
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Acid or base-catalyzed dehydration then leads to α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compounds.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The combination of these two steps is known as the aldol condensation.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The Prins reaction occurs when a nucleophilic alkene or alkyne reacts with an aldehyde as electrophile.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The product of the Prins reaction varies with reaction conditions and substrates employed.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] This reaction is used as a test for aldehydes and is useful for separation or purification of aldehydes.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] A **dialdehyde** is an organic chemical compound with two aldehyde groups.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The nomenclature of dialdehydes have the ending *-dial* or sometimes *-dialdehyde*.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Short aliphatic dialdehydes are sometimes named after the diacid from which they can be derived.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] An example is butanedial, which is also called succinaldehyde (from succinic acid).
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Some aldehydes are substrates for aldehyde dehydrogenase enzymes which metabolize aldehydes in the body.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] There are toxicities associated with some aldehydes that are related to neurodegenerative disease, heart disease, and some types of cancer.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Of all aldehydes, formaldehyde is produced on the largest scale, about 6000000 tons per year.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] It is mainly used in the production of resins when combined with urea, melamine, and phenol (e.g., Bakelite).
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] It is a precursor to methylene diphenyl diisocyanate ("MDI"), a precursor to polyurethanes.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The second main aldehyde is butyraldehyde, of which about 2500000 tons per year are prepared by hydroformylation.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] It is the principal precursor to 2-ethylhexanol, which is used as a plasticizer.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Acetaldehyde once was a dominating product, but production levels have declined to less than 1000000 tons per year because it mainly served as a precursor to acetic acid, which is now prepared by carbonylation of methanol.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Many other aldehydes find commercial applications, often as precursors to alcohols, the so-called oxo alcohols, which are used in detergents.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Some aldehydes are produced only on a small scale (less than 1000 tons per year) and are used as ingredients in flavours and perfumes such as Chanel No.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Fresh, green, citrusy and nutty notes in perfumes are often due to aldehydes.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] These include cinnamaldehyde and its derivatives, citral, and lilial.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The common names for aldehydes do not strictly follow official guidelines, such as those recommended by IUPAC, but these rules are useful.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In other cases, such as when a −CHO group is attached to a ring, the suffix *-carbaldehyde* may be used.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] Thus, C6H11CHO is known as *cyclohexanecarbaldehyde*.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] If the presence of another functional group demands the use of a suffix, the aldehyde group is named with the prefix *formyl-*.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] This prefix is preferred to *methanoyl-*.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] If the compound is a natural product or a carboxylic acid, the prefix *oxo-* may be used to indicate which carbon atom is part of the aldehyde group; for example, CHOCH2COOH is named *2-oxoethanoic acid*.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] If replacing the aldehyde group with a carboxyl group (−COOH) would yield a carboxylic acid with a trivial name, the aldehyde may be named by replacing the suffix *-ic acid* or *-oic acid* in this trivial name by *-aldehyde*.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The word *aldehyde* was coined by Justus von Liebig as a contraction of the Latin ***al**cohol **dehyd**rogenatus* (dehydrogenated alcohol).
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] In the past, aldehydes were sometimes named after the corresponding alcohols, for example, *vinous aldehyde* for acetaldehyde.
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] The term *formyl group* is derived from the Latin word *formica* "ant".
[src:aldehyde/aldehyde] This word can be recognized in the simplest aldehyde, formaldehyde, and in the simplest carboxylic acid, formic acid.
